      {
        "paragraph_index": 2,
        "text": "### Chemical Insight\n\nThe overwhelming dominance of Fe³⁺ is expected from the **Irving–Williams series** and hard–soft acid–base (HSAB) theory. Fe³⁺ is a harder, more highly charged Lewis acid (charge-to-radius ratio ≈ 4.6 vs. ≈ 2.6 for Fe²⁺), so it forms stronger electrostatic bonds with the O- and N-donor ligands that dominate this dataset. The sole near-exception — **2,2′-bipyridyl** — is a classic π-acceptor ligand that stabilises the lower oxidation state through metal-to-ligand back-bonding, which explains why Fe²⁺ can match Fe³⁺ here. In practice, the famous deep-red [Fe(bipy)₃]²⁺ complex is far more kinetically stable than its Fe³⁺ analogue, even if the thermodynamic log β values are comparable.\n\n*Source: NIST Standard Reference Database 46 (Critically Selected Stability Constants of Metal Complexes).*",
        "claims": [
          {
            "start": 0,
            "end": 20,
            "text": "### Chemical Insight",
            "claim_type": "filler",
            "metadata": {
